WEBVTT

00:01.710 --> 00:04.671
[fire hissing]

00:06.131 --> 00:07.466
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:07.466 --> 00:09.134
<i>‐ Last time on</i>
<i>"Forged in Fire,"</i>

00:09.134 --> 00:11.220
<i>seven former competitors</i>
<i>put it all on the line</i>

00:11.220 --> 00:13.513
<i>seeking redemption, $20,000,</i>

00:13.513 --> 00:16.308
<i>and another shot at the title</i>
<i>"Forged in Fire" champion.</i>

00:16.308 --> 00:17.684
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:17.684 --> 00:19.603
<i>But in one of</i>
<i>the toughest challenges</i>

00:19.603 --> 00:22.481
<i>in "Forged in Fire" history,</i>
<i>three smiths have fallen.</i>

00:22.481 --> 00:25.859
<i>Only four smiths remain</i>
<i>a step closer to the end</i>

00:25.859 --> 00:28.487
<i>of a long road to redemption.</i>

00:28.487 --> 00:30.322
<i>Aaron Morrison...</i>

00:30.322 --> 00:33.200
<i>‐ So far, these challenges</i>
<i>have been no joke.</i>

00:33.200 --> 00:35.327
We've had to do a lot
to get here,

00:35.327 --> 00:37.454
<i>but the journey</i>
<i>is always long</i>

00:37.454 --> 00:38.997
<i>for things that</i>
<i>are worth doing,</i>

00:38.997 --> 00:40.999
and this is definitely
worth doing.

00:40.999 --> 00:42.668
‐ [grunts]
<i>‐ If I can win this title,</i>

00:42.668 --> 00:44.586
<i>then that really shows that</i>
<i>I've earned it</i>

00:44.586 --> 00:47.172
and that I know what
I'm talking about.

00:47.172 --> 00:48.840
<i>‐ David Sowards‐Emmerd.</i>

00:48.840 --> 00:50.551
‐ The road to redemption
has been a long one,

00:50.551 --> 00:52.469
<i>both mental and physical.</i>

00:52.469 --> 00:54.471
The first challenge was
all physical.

00:54.471 --> 00:56.598
I'm forging a lot slower
than I usually would.

00:56.598 --> 00:59.017
<i>So far, it's going great,</i>
<i>but there's a long road ahead,</i>

00:59.017 --> 01:00.727
and I'm ready for whatever
they throw at me.

01:00.727 --> 01:02.521
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:02.521 --> 01:04.189
<i>‐ Matt Berry.</i>

01:04.189 --> 01:06.066
‐ Matt, this is a nice piece.

01:06.066 --> 01:07.359
‐ Thank you.

01:07.359 --> 01:08.860
<i>‐ Now that we're down</i>
<i>to four,</i>

01:08.860 --> 01:10.904
<i>you can't just count</i>
<i>on surviving.</i>

01:10.904 --> 01:13.949
You actually have to put out
something good.

01:13.949 --> 01:16.201
You actually have
to beat other people.

01:16.201 --> 01:18.120
<i>Now it's getting</i>
<i>fairly intense.</i>

01:18.120 --> 01:20.038
I want this.
I want the validation

01:20.038 --> 01:21.832
that I'm good at this.

01:21.832 --> 01:23.834
‐ And Chris Price.

01:23.834 --> 01:26.128
‐ I'm doing this for the people
who watch this competition

01:26.128 --> 01:27.921
and fall in love
with our craft.

01:27.921 --> 01:29.423
[clanging]

01:29.423 --> 01:31.049
<i>Kids in hospitals who</i>
<i>turn on this show</i>

01:31.049 --> 01:32.175
<i>and see what we're doing</i>

01:32.175 --> 01:33.719
<i>and get excited about it‐‐</i>

01:33.719 --> 01:35.220
that motivates me.

01:35.220 --> 01:36.555
[whirring]

01:36.555 --> 01:38.640
<i>For me, redemption means</i>
<i>that the people</i>

01:38.640 --> 01:40.559
who have faith in me
are right.

01:40.559 --> 01:43.478
<i>‐ Which smith has what it</i>
<i>takes to earn redemption?</i>

01:43.478 --> 01:44.438
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:44.438 --> 01:45.605
<i>Who has the skill,</i>

01:45.605 --> 01:47.024
<i>drive, and determination</i>

01:47.024 --> 01:48.817
<i>to earn the title</i>
<i>and 20 grand?</i>

01:48.817 --> 01:50.068
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:50.068 --> 01:51.653
<i>The epic conclusion</i>

01:51.653 --> 01:53.697
<i>of the "Long Road to</i>
<i>Redemption" starts...</i>

01:53.697 --> 01:55.824
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:55.824 --> 01:56.825
<i>Now.</i>

01:56.825 --> 01:59.077
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:59.077 --> 02:01.038
Bladesmiths, welcome back.

02:01.038 --> 02:02.497
Congratulations.
You've made it

02:02.497 --> 02:04.458
into the next evolution
of this competition,

02:04.458 --> 02:07.586
which means that you're
one step closer to redemption.

02:07.586 --> 02:09.171
However,
the long road to redemption

02:09.171 --> 02:12.090
will only become rougher
and less familiar.

02:12.090 --> 02:14.426
It's time to ramp things up
a little bit.

02:14.426 --> 02:16.011
In this round
of competition,

02:16.011 --> 02:19.056
you'll be using the steel
that's on your anvils.

02:19.056 --> 02:21.016
Go ahead and lift up
that cloth.

02:21.016 --> 02:23.435
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:23.435 --> 02:25.979
This is a round of W1 steel

02:25.979 --> 02:27.773
approximately 6 inches long.

02:27.773 --> 02:29.274
In this round of competition,

02:29.274 --> 02:31.526
you're not just gonna
mash metal to any shape.

02:31.526 --> 02:34.655
Instead, we've got
to custom order one of these.

02:34.655 --> 02:36.990
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:36.990 --> 02:38.450
A jambiya.

02:38.450 --> 02:40.452
It must be an effective version
of this weapon

02:40.452 --> 02:43.080
that is between
8 and 10 inches in length

02:43.080 --> 02:45.290
with a central ridge.

02:45.290 --> 02:47.000
‐ Holy [bleep].

02:47.000 --> 02:49.544
<i>I've seen them.</i>
<i>I've never tried them</i>

02:49.544 --> 02:52.130
<i>'cause they have</i>
<i>that pronounced medial ridge,</i>

02:52.130 --> 02:55.425
and that just looks
really hard to forge.

02:55.425 --> 02:56.968
‐ Keep in mind,
in the second round,

02:56.968 --> 02:58.637
you'll be attaching
handles to those blades

02:58.637 --> 03:00.639
to turn them into
fully functional weapons.

03:00.639 --> 03:04.935
They'll be tested for strength
and durability in a horn chop

03:04.935 --> 03:08.605
and for edge retention in
a rib rack slice.

03:08.605 --> 03:10.315
You'll have three hours
in this round.

03:10.315 --> 03:13.110
Do your best work, because
after you finish this round

03:13.110 --> 03:15.445
and the judges have evaluated
your blades,

03:15.445 --> 03:17.197
one of you will have to
surrender your blade

03:17.197 --> 03:18.657
and leave The Forge

03:18.657 --> 03:21.868
Good luck, bladesmiths.
Your three hours starts now.

03:21.868 --> 03:23.954
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:23.954 --> 03:25.455
‐ Here we go.

03:25.455 --> 03:28.500
‐ These guys have to create
a central ridge

03:28.500 --> 03:30.001
in this blade.

03:30.001 --> 03:33.046
Do you do that late,
or do you do it early?

03:33.046 --> 03:35.006
‐ Right off the bat,
this is one of those situations

03:35.006 --> 03:37.300
where I'd forge thick,
grind thin.

03:37.300 --> 03:38.802
Get your shape,

03:38.802 --> 03:40.512
get everything fullered up
to the size you need,

03:40.512 --> 03:42.514
and then take an angle grinder
and flap wheels

03:42.514 --> 03:44.724
and just knock the rest of it
down and clean it up.

03:44.724 --> 03:45.851
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:45.851 --> 03:47.269
<i>‐ I have to make a jambiya.</i>

03:47.269 --> 03:48.353
I've seen lots of them.

03:48.353 --> 03:49.688
I'm familiar with the form.

03:49.688 --> 03:51.148
<i>They're not really easy</i>
<i>to make,</i>

03:51.148 --> 03:52.691
<i>but people make them</i>
<i>all the time</i>

03:52.691 --> 03:54.484
in third‐world countries
with minimal tooling,

03:54.484 --> 03:56.027
so I've got no excuse here.

03:56.027 --> 03:58.113
‐ Historically, these are
blades that are found

03:58.113 --> 04:00.198
in Persia, the Middle East,
and India.

04:00.198 --> 04:01.950
It's also known as a khanjar.

04:01.950 --> 04:04.119
Now, these blades
are typically daggers,

04:04.119 --> 04:05.620
not big blades.

04:05.620 --> 04:06.997
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:06.997 --> 04:08.582
<i>‐ My game plan is</i>
<i>to make a tool</i>

04:08.582 --> 04:10.709
<i>to help me build</i>
<i>that ridge into my steel.</i>

04:10.709 --> 04:12.794
‐ Chris made a horseshoe.

04:12.794 --> 04:14.588
Why?
‐ For luck.

04:14.588 --> 04:15.964
[all laughing]

04:15.964 --> 04:17.132
‐ He's making it a jig

04:17.132 --> 04:18.717
that's he's gonna
use on the press

04:18.717 --> 04:20.719
or on the power hammer
to get that central ridge.

04:20.719 --> 04:22.387
If you were gonna make
a hundred jambiya,

04:22.387 --> 04:24.473
you would have jigs set up all
over the place for it.

04:24.473 --> 04:27.225
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:27.225 --> 04:32.063
‐ This road to redemption has
been no easy travel, for sure.

04:32.063 --> 04:33.815
‐ Look at Aaron's floor
right there.

04:33.815 --> 04:36.067
He's got the entire knife drawn
out on the floor in chalk.

04:36.067 --> 04:39.738
‐ Our only competitor to have
failed parameters twice

04:39.738 --> 04:41.239
in a single competition.

04:41.239 --> 04:43.241
<i>‐ I've never made</i>
<i>a jambiya before!</i>

04:43.241 --> 04:46.328
You know, now I gotta make one
in three hours or less.

04:46.328 --> 04:48.079
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:48.079 --> 04:50.165
<i>The hardest part about it is</i>
<i>creating a central spine.</i>

04:50.165 --> 04:51.708
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:51.708 --> 04:54.961
<i>‐ I actually feel good</i>
<i>being back in the forge.</i>

04:54.961 --> 04:57.589
We've got gas forges,
we've got grinders,

04:57.589 --> 04:59.841
and we've got power hammers.

04:59.841 --> 05:01.676
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:01.676 --> 05:05.305
The game plan is, first, get
the stock reduced down

05:05.305 --> 05:06.973
to a size that I can work.

05:06.973 --> 05:11.436
Second stage is to start
rough‐shaping the dagger‐‐

05:11.436 --> 05:12.771
jambiya, whatever it is.

05:12.771 --> 05:14.773
<i>This is gonna be really hard,</i>

05:14.773 --> 05:16.274
especially in three hours.

05:16.274 --> 05:18.318
[clang]

05:18.318 --> 05:19.778
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:19.778 --> 05:22.614
‐ The actual knife...

05:22.614 --> 05:24.574
never seen anything like
that before.

05:24.574 --> 05:26.952
<i>It looks interesting but, uh,</i>
<i>it's going to be a challenge.</i>

05:26.952 --> 05:29.955
‐ David's heading over
to big blue.

05:29.955 --> 05:31.623
<i>‐ I just want to get</i>
<i>the length first</i>

05:31.623 --> 05:33.708
and then start
to define a handle.

05:33.708 --> 05:36.044
All right,
there's plenty of blade.

05:36.044 --> 05:38.880
Now I can chop off
whatever's left.

05:38.880 --> 05:40.423
[buzzing]

05:40.423 --> 05:41.716
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:41.716 --> 05:43.510
‐ I'm concerned about
David, here.

05:43.510 --> 05:46.221
He's cut off a good chunk
of, like, 4 inches of metal

05:46.221 --> 05:48.139
and his blade's looking
really thin.

05:48.139 --> 05:50.225
He's really going to have
to pull those bevels out

05:50.225 --> 05:51.893
to get some width
in that blade.

05:51.893 --> 05:53.812
‐ Chopping the steel off early,
it means I don't spend

05:53.812 --> 05:55.647
as long heating up stuff
in the forge.

05:55.647 --> 05:57.274
I'm not concerned about
chopping off steel

05:57.274 --> 05:59.568
because my handle right now
is still very thick,

05:59.568 --> 06:01.820
<i>so I've got lots</i>
<i>of extra material there.</i>

06:01.820 --> 06:03.071
So far, so good.

06:03.071 --> 06:04.447
That's more reasonable.

06:04.447 --> 06:07.075
‐ Bladesmiths,
one hour has elapsed!

06:07.075 --> 06:09.369
You have two hours remaining
to finish your work!

06:09.369 --> 06:11.621
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:11.621 --> 06:14.040
The one feature of this knife

06:14.040 --> 06:18.003
that is really concerning me
is that central ridge.

06:18.003 --> 06:21.715
Not a single one of these
smiths has set up for it,

06:21.715 --> 06:24.676
with the exception
of maybe Chris.

06:24.676 --> 06:27.679
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:27.679 --> 06:29.180
<i>‐ I can't let the</i>
<i>key feature‐‐</i>

06:29.180 --> 06:30.807
this medial ridge‐‐
be an afterthought.

06:30.807 --> 06:32.601
It's got to be my priority
for this knife,

06:32.601 --> 06:34.311
<i>so I forge it to shape.</i>

06:34.311 --> 06:36.730
‐ It looks like Chris has got
something down the center.

06:36.730 --> 06:38.481
‐ Yeah, it's very beefy.

06:38.481 --> 06:42.444
‐ Watching Chris pay so much
attention to detail,

06:42.444 --> 06:43.862
now I remember...

06:43.862 --> 06:45.405
I'll go as far as saying

06:45.405 --> 06:49.034
it's the sexiest saxe
I've ever seen turned in.

06:49.034 --> 06:50.660
[ all laughing]

06:50.660 --> 06:51.703
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:51.703 --> 06:53.079
<i>‐ In my first competition,</i>

06:53.079 --> 06:54.539
I did not succeed because

06:54.539 --> 06:57.292
the socket on my lion spear
was too small,

06:57.292 --> 06:59.377
<i>which turned out</i>
<i>to be catastrophic.</i>

06:59.377 --> 07:02.047
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:02.047 --> 07:04.466
<i>I'm just not gonna let</i>
<i>a small detail</i>

07:04.466 --> 07:05.884
send me home this time.

07:05.884 --> 07:08.219
I am going to be as paranoid
about this stuff

07:08.219 --> 07:10.472
as I possibly can.

07:10.472 --> 07:12.015
<i>So I'm starting</i>
<i>to get the shape in it,</i>

07:12.015 --> 07:15.060
and I notice there's a line
in my billet.

07:15.060 --> 07:16.269
Oh, come on.

07:16.269 --> 07:17.729
<i>Being paranoid, I'm like,</i>

07:17.729 --> 07:21.066
"Wait, is this what's going
to send me home?"

07:21.066 --> 07:24.277
So I bend it away
from the line

07:24.277 --> 07:28.073
to see if it's really a crack
or if it's just a line.

07:28.073 --> 07:29.449
[clanging]

07:29.449 --> 07:31.242
And I can see the metal
start to separate.

07:31.242 --> 07:32.827
[beep]!

07:32.827 --> 07:35.246
<i>If this is a crack</i>
<i>and I forge it into my blade,</i>

07:35.246 --> 07:36.706
my blade's going
to snap in half.

07:36.706 --> 07:38.625
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:38.625 --> 07:41.294
‐ I'm guessing he had a crack
there that he saw,

07:41.294 --> 07:43.755
and he cut about a good 4
or 5 inches

07:43.755 --> 07:45.423
off the end of his blade.

07:45.423 --> 07:47.342
‐ I have less material now
than I did two minutes ago,

07:47.342 --> 07:48.927
but I still think
I can make it.

07:48.927 --> 07:50.970
[clanging]

07:51.513 --> 07:53.431
<i>‐ Pressure's definitely on.</i>

07:53.431 --> 07:56.351
I feel like I'm really behind
other people.

07:56.351 --> 07:57.644
Whoo, there we go.

07:57.644 --> 08:00.230
My next step is
to draw from center,

08:00.230 --> 08:01.981
establishing
that central spine.

08:01.981 --> 08:02.982
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:02.982 --> 08:04.401
<i>I'm definitely feeling</i>

08:04.401 --> 08:05.694
<i>the pressure</i>
<i>of the clock right now.</i>

08:05.694 --> 08:07.612
I still got a lot
of stuff to do

08:07.612 --> 08:09.280
and a short time
to do it in.

08:09.280 --> 08:10.782
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:10.782 --> 08:12.409
<i>‐ I've never put a ridge in</i>
<i>a knife before.</i>

08:12.409 --> 08:14.494
It's going to be interesting
to forge this out.

08:14.494 --> 08:16.246
‐ These things better be
strong, and that rib

08:16.246 --> 08:18.123
is what's going to make
to make that knife strong.

08:18.123 --> 08:20.291
<i>‐ So I'm trying to use</i>
<i>the spring fuller first</i>

08:20.291 --> 08:21.668
to establish my ridge.

08:21.668 --> 08:23.211
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:23.211 --> 08:25.255
I don't think that's
gonna work.

08:25.255 --> 08:26.840
This is not working with
the spring fuller,

08:26.840 --> 08:29.300
<i>so I need an alternate way</i>
<i>to do this.</i>

08:29.300 --> 08:31.136
<i>My alternate plan is</i>
<i>to just use</i>

08:31.136 --> 08:33.805
the edge of the die
of the hydraulic press.

08:33.805 --> 08:35.265
‐ Looks like he's getting
a little bit

08:35.265 --> 08:36.808
of the rib in there.
He's‐‐he's getting

08:36.808 --> 08:38.476
the shape right,
but it's still a narrow blade.

08:38.476 --> 08:41.563
‐ I think David's realizing
he's in deep doo‐doo.

08:41.563 --> 08:44.190
Big mistake chopping off
that piece of steel.

08:44.190 --> 08:46.568
‐ It always surprises me
that not many bladesmiths

08:46.568 --> 08:47.986
use the crossbeam
in their hammer.

08:47.986 --> 08:49.487
I mean, this would be
the perfect time.

08:49.487 --> 08:51.156
You lay half of it
on your anvil,

08:51.156 --> 08:53.408
you crossbeam away from
the central ridge,

08:53.408 --> 08:54.993
leaving that ridge
without being hit.

08:54.993 --> 08:56.369
[clanging]

08:56.369 --> 08:57.996
‐ Bladesmiths,

08:57.996 --> 08:59.831
you've only got 60 minutes
remaining

08:59.831 --> 09:01.374
to finish your jambiyas!

09:01.374 --> 09:02.459
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:02.459 --> 09:04.210
‐ I have a little W1 left,

09:04.210 --> 09:06.504
and because I don't know its
chemistry, I'm gonna test it.

09:06.504 --> 09:08.048
<i>It's the only way</i>
<i>to understand</i>

09:08.048 --> 09:09.507
<i>how to do a good heat treat.</i>

09:09.507 --> 09:11.092
If you heat it up,
normalize it,

09:11.092 --> 09:12.594
break it,
look at the grain inside.

09:12.594 --> 09:14.179
Do that maybe a couple
of times to make sure

09:14.179 --> 09:16.389
that the knife
turns out the way I want it.

09:16.389 --> 09:18.016
‐ Chris has a habit
of testing everything

09:18.016 --> 09:19.392
he gets his hands on.

09:19.392 --> 09:21.269
Chris did what I've been
waiting four seasons

09:21.269 --> 09:22.812
for somebody to do.

09:22.812 --> 09:25.273
He took recycled material,
heated it, quenched it,

09:25.273 --> 09:27.108
and snapped it to see
the grain structure.

09:27.108 --> 09:30.528
That's going to tell him how
he should heat treat the blade.

09:30.528 --> 09:34.199
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:34.199 --> 09:36.534
‐ That's some ugly big grain.

09:36.534 --> 09:38.536
I take my test piece
and get it hot again,

09:38.536 --> 09:39.829
<i>quench it a second time.</i>

09:39.829 --> 09:40.955
<i>When I break it then...</i>

09:40.955 --> 09:43.541
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:43.541 --> 09:44.667
<i>It looks better.</i>

09:44.667 --> 09:46.127
Not good. Better.

09:46.127 --> 09:48.046
By double‐quenching W1,

09:48.046 --> 09:50.048
that's going to give me
a nice, hard blade

09:50.048 --> 09:52.050
with a nice, tight
grain structure.

09:52.050 --> 09:54.511
[sizzling]

09:54.511 --> 10:01.643
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:04.813 --> 10:06.147
Looking good.

10:06.147 --> 10:07.649
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:07.649 --> 10:09.025
<i>‐ The grinder's where</i>

10:09.025 --> 10:10.485
<i>I'm gonna put in</i>
<i>the medial ridge.</i>

10:10.485 --> 10:12.362
‐ Now that's just
a good adjustment

10:12.362 --> 10:15.281
from a smith who knows there
are multiple tools in his shop

10:15.281 --> 10:17.742
that can accomplish
the same tasks.

10:17.742 --> 10:19.828
‐ I've got to not grind
the ridge,

10:19.828 --> 10:23.498
but I have to grind everything
else away so there is a ridge.

10:23.498 --> 10:25.750
‐ It would be a lot easier
to put that ridge in

10:25.750 --> 10:27.293
while the blade is straight.

10:27.293 --> 10:29.420
‐ You really need a totally
steady hand and eye

10:29.420 --> 10:32.799
to be able to match everything
up on both sides.

10:32.799 --> 10:35.593
<i>‐ It's probably the hardest</i>
<i>grind I've ever done.</i>

10:35.593 --> 10:36.928
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:36.928 --> 10:38.888
‐ Wow!
‐ In less than ten minutes,

10:38.888 --> 10:41.266
Matt was able to put
that central ridge,

10:41.266 --> 10:42.642
and it looks good.

10:42.642 --> 10:44.144
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:44.144 --> 10:45.895
<i>‐ I think I can get</i>
<i>some extra work done</i>

10:45.895 --> 10:49.315
for the next round now by
drilling holes in the handle.

10:49.315 --> 10:50.733
<i>This is where I had</i>

10:50.733 --> 10:51.985
<i>catastrophic failure</i>
<i>last time‐‐</i>

10:51.985 --> 10:53.236
<i>in exactly the same place.</i>

10:53.236 --> 10:54.737
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:54.737 --> 10:56.281
[clanging]

10:56.281 --> 10:58.074
So I'm a little hesitant
about drilling holes.

10:58.074 --> 10:59.284
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:59.284 --> 11:00.577
Now it's gonna work.

11:00.577 --> 11:03.454
So I drill holes
and, you know, no issue.

11:03.454 --> 11:04.539
I'm ready to quench.

11:04.539 --> 11:06.040
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:06.040 --> 11:08.334
‐ All right,
David's in the quench.

11:08.334 --> 11:09.544
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:09.544 --> 11:10.962
‐ Dave's profile from here‐‐

11:10.962 --> 11:14.465
it's not jambiya‐like.
It's, like, banana‐like.

11:14.465 --> 11:15.800
‐ It's straight,
it's quenched,

11:15.800 --> 11:18.553
and it's got a ridge
and a handle.

11:18.553 --> 11:20.221
So far, it's looking good.

11:20.221 --> 11:21.806
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:21.806 --> 11:23.558
<i>‐ There's about 12 minutes</i>
<i>left on the clock.</i>

11:23.558 --> 11:26.102
It's do or die time
for a quench.

11:26.102 --> 11:27.687
<i>Still not</i>
<i>the most amount of time</i>

11:27.687 --> 11:30.231
that I would really like
to have for a good quench,

11:30.231 --> 11:32.150
<i>but 12 minutes is</i>
<i>a long time</i>

11:32.150 --> 11:33.818
if you're underwater
or on fire.

11:33.818 --> 11:36.112
<i>If I have any problems</i>
<i>right now,</i>

11:36.112 --> 11:37.614
that's going to send me back,

11:37.614 --> 11:39.490
and I don't have time
to make that up at all.

11:39.490 --> 11:42.994
‐ Aaron, just trying to get an
even temperature on his blade.

11:42.994 --> 11:44.954
<i>‐ I don't have time</i>
<i>to correct this.</i>

11:44.954 --> 11:47.081
I don't have time
to straighten it.

11:47.081 --> 11:49.209
I don't have time
for a re‐quench.

11:49.209 --> 11:52.670
This quench has to be
<i>the</i> quench.

11:56.466 --> 11:57.800
‐ There he is.

11:57.800 --> 12:00.094
Aaron in the quench.

12:00.094 --> 12:03.014
‐ I file test it,
and it skates.

12:03.014 --> 12:07.310
I'm excited,
but I feel overwhelmed.

12:07.310 --> 12:10.521
‐ Five, four, three,

12:10.521 --> 12:12.190
two, one.

12:12.190 --> 12:14.108
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines!

12:14.108 --> 12:15.360
Stop what you're doing!

12:15.360 --> 12:18.446
This round of competition
is over!

12:18.446 --> 12:19.572
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:19.572 --> 12:21.032
<i>‐ I'm looking at other blades,</i>

12:21.032 --> 12:23.117
<i>and I really feel</i>
<i>out of place.</i>

12:23.117 --> 12:26.871
Chris has a ridiculously
cool‐looking jambiya.

12:26.871 --> 12:29.040
<i>I think Dave did really well.</i>

12:29.040 --> 12:30.250
<i>I'm sure Matt did well.</i>

12:30.250 --> 12:31.834
<i>I think I'm behind the curve,</i>

12:31.834 --> 12:34.462
<i>which could be grounds</i>
<i>for me to go home.</i>

12:34.462 --> 12:35.588
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:35.588 --> 12:37.340
‐ All right, bladesmiths,

12:37.340 --> 12:40.134
it's time for the judges to
take a look at your jambiyas.

12:40.134 --> 12:41.636
Matt, you're up first.

12:41.636 --> 12:43.554
Please present your blade
to the judges.

12:43.554 --> 12:45.098
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:45.098 --> 12:47.225
<i>‐ Well, Matt, I love</i>
<i>the profile of your blade,</i>

12:47.225 --> 12:49.519
<i>especially your handle</i>
<i>where it's got a catch</i>

12:49.519 --> 12:51.729
to where it allows me
to hold onto the blade‐‐

12:51.729 --> 12:53.773
you know, especially
this, when we're slashing

12:53.773 --> 12:55.650
or stabbing with the blade.

12:55.650 --> 12:57.318
Uh, great grinding skills.

12:57.318 --> 12:58.778
‐ Thank you.
‐ To be able to find a way

12:58.778 --> 13:00.446
to get the ridge in there
from grinding...

13:00.446 --> 13:02.031
it did pick up a little bit
of a warp.

13:02.031 --> 13:04.409
If you move forward,
you can adjust that,

13:04.409 --> 13:06.035
but overall, good job.

13:06.035 --> 13:07.829
‐ Thank you.
‐ David, you're up.

13:07.829 --> 13:10.164
Please present your blade
to the judges.

13:10.164 --> 13:12.000
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:12.000 --> 13:13.668
<i>‐ Well, David, it's straight,</i>

13:13.668 --> 13:15.420
<i>but your handle is a</i>
<i>bit on the lean side.</i>

13:15.420 --> 13:17.922
You don't have that mass
in the front or back.

13:17.922 --> 13:19.966
You don't have a lot of width
right here, also.

13:19.966 --> 13:21.968
I'm guessing you wish you
didn't cut off

13:21.968 --> 13:24.470
that 4 inches of steel
or whatever in the beginning

13:24.470 --> 13:26.514
because it left you less
to work with.

13:26.514 --> 13:28.599
<i>You do have the rib</i>
<i>in there, though.</i>

13:28.599 --> 13:29.726
<i>It's a little undefined.</i>

13:29.726 --> 13:31.436
Definitely could use more work.

13:31.436 --> 13:32.854
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:32.854 --> 13:34.772
‐ Chris, you're up.
Please present your blade

13:34.772 --> 13:35.773
to the judges.

13:35.773 --> 13:37.108
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:37.108 --> 13:38.526
<i>‐ Well, Chris,</i>
<i>there's undeniably</i>

13:38.526 --> 13:39.777
<i>a lot of steel here.</i>

13:39.777 --> 13:41.320
The handle is really narrow
as well.

13:41.320 --> 13:42.947
<i>If you move on to</i>
<i>the next round,</i>

13:42.947 --> 13:44.866
it's gonna be interesting to
see if you can make that

13:44.866 --> 13:45.950
into something comfortable.

13:45.950 --> 13:46.993
And if you do move on

13:46.993 --> 13:48.161
to the next round,

13:48.161 --> 13:49.829
please do something with
this weight.

13:49.829 --> 13:52.248
It is a heavy, heavy knife.

13:52.248 --> 13:54.042
‐ All right, Aaron,
please present your blade

13:54.042 --> 13:55.168
to the judges.

13:55.168 --> 13:56.544
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:56.544 --> 13:58.588
<i>‐ Aaron, you did it.</i>
<i>[chuckling]</i>

13:58.588 --> 14:00.423
You stayed within
the parameters!

14:00.423 --> 14:03.051
Not only that, you figured
things out that we do.

14:03.051 --> 14:05.595
I like the overall profile
of your blade,

14:05.595 --> 14:09.098
but it does need some defining
features over there to make it

14:09.098 --> 14:10.641
a balanced blade.

14:10.641 --> 14:11.601
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:11.601 --> 14:13.144
Good job.
‐ Thanks.

14:13.144 --> 14:14.812
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:14.812 --> 14:17.148
‐ Bladesmiths, the judges have
made their final decision.

14:17.148 --> 14:18.483
For one of you,

14:18.483 --> 14:20.735
the road to redemption
ends right now.

14:20.735 --> 14:22.987
The bladesmith leaving
The Forge is...

14:22.987 --> 14:26.866
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:26.866 --> 14:29.619
David.
Your blade didn't make the cut.

14:29.619 --> 14:32.413
‐ David, we really commend you
for making it this far

14:32.413 --> 14:33.998
for this road to redemption,

14:33.998 --> 14:36.000
but unfortunately, your blade
was the least refined

14:36.000 --> 14:38.211
compared to
your other competitors.

14:38.211 --> 14:40.004
And for that reason,
we're sending you home.

14:40.004 --> 14:41.339
‐ I understand.

14:41.339 --> 14:43.633
‐ David,
it's a tough challenge.

14:43.633 --> 14:44.842
Hold your head high,

14:44.842 --> 14:46.677
but please surrender
your blade.

14:46.677 --> 14:48.387
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:48.387 --> 14:50.681
<i>‐ The road to redemption</i>
<i>is a long one in this case‐‐</i>

14:50.681 --> 14:52.850
<i>a very long one.</i>
<i>And I made good progress,</i>

14:52.850 --> 14:54.352
but I didn't make it
to the end.

14:54.352 --> 14:55.895
<i>For the rest</i>
<i>of the three smiths‐‐</i>

14:55.895 --> 14:57.271
<i>and all of them in general,</i>
<i>I mean‐‐</i>

14:57.271 --> 14:59.023
good luck and keep doing it.

14:59.023 --> 15:01.526
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:01.526 --> 15:03.361
‐ Bladesmiths,
congratulations.

15:03.361 --> 15:05.947
You've made it into the next
stage of this competition,

15:05.947 --> 15:07.657
and now that those blades
have been tempered,

15:07.657 --> 15:10.076
it's time to turn them
into fully functional jambiyas

15:10.076 --> 15:11.702
by attaching handles to them.

15:11.702 --> 15:14.539
You can only use
natural materials,

15:14.539 --> 15:19.043
and you must include
four florets on your jambiyas.

15:19.043 --> 15:20.545
You'll have three
hours in this round

15:20.545 --> 15:22.004
in which to do your work.

15:22.004 --> 15:23.673
Use your time wisely,
because after this,

15:23.673 --> 15:26.050
we'll be testing them
for strength and durability

15:26.050 --> 15:27.301
in a horn chop...

15:27.301 --> 15:28.719
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:28.719 --> 15:31.264
And for edge retention
in a rib rack slice.

15:31.264 --> 15:32.807
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:32.807 --> 15:34.892
After this round and
your blades have been tested,

15:34.892 --> 15:37.478
one of you will have
to surrender your jambiya

15:37.478 --> 15:39.188
and leave The Forge.

15:39.188 --> 15:42.316
Good luck, gentlemen.
Your three hours starts now.

15:42.316 --> 15:43.901
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:43.901 --> 15:47.196
‐ Many cultures use the jambiya
pretty much as a status.

15:47.196 --> 15:49.448
The more decorative
the handle, the better

15:49.448 --> 15:51.993
because that dictates
your status in society.

15:51.993 --> 15:53.536
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:53.536 --> 15:56.414
‐ Matt has chosen some sort
of wood block to use

15:56.414 --> 15:58.082
as his handle material.

15:58.082 --> 16:00.418
<i>‐ I don't want to attempt</i>
<i>horn, bone, antler,</i>

16:00.418 --> 16:03.296
or any of that crap 'cause
that's all harder to work with.

16:03.296 --> 16:04.380
[tool buzzing]

16:04.380 --> 16:05.631
Oh!

16:05.631 --> 16:07.967
As I'm pushing my slab,
it's drifting.

16:07.967 --> 16:09.510
Come on.

16:09.510 --> 16:10.928
<i>If my pieces aren't even,</i>

16:10.928 --> 16:12.221
then I'm going to have
a handle

16:12.221 --> 16:14.265
that doesn't really grip
the user's hand.

16:14.265 --> 16:17.977
<i>I just say, "Screw it,"</i>
<i>and I go and get a chisel.</i>

16:17.977 --> 16:19.437
Whee!

16:19.437 --> 16:20.646
I got stuff to work with.

16:20.646 --> 16:23.858
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:23.858 --> 16:26.944
‐ Chris and Matt have both
gone to the final round.

16:26.944 --> 16:28.654
I haven't.

16:28.654 --> 16:31.157
<i>It's really up to me to really</i>
<i>display what I can do</i>

16:31.157 --> 16:32.783
against these big dogs.

16:32.783 --> 16:35.786
I'm cleaning up the spine,
cleaning up the transitions‐‐

16:35.786 --> 16:39.624
I got a lot of work to do and
a short time to do it in.

16:39.624 --> 16:41.334
<i>I'm really concerned about</i>
<i>the florets,</i>

16:41.334 --> 16:43.794
but I can't worry about that
at all.

16:43.794 --> 16:46.297
<i>I have to clean up the grinds</i>
<i>before I do anything else.</i>

16:46.297 --> 16:49.175
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:49.175 --> 16:51.636
‐ Chris is trying
to lighten the load.

16:51.636 --> 16:54.388
‐ Yeah, Chris's knife
is very heavy.

16:54.388 --> 16:57.266
<i>‐ I budgeted about an hour to</i>
<i>address the judge's concerns</i>

16:57.266 --> 16:59.894
with my blade and get it
looking like a proper jambiya.

16:59.894 --> 17:01.312
‐ Oh yeah,
this is my little friend.

17:01.312 --> 17:03.231
He helps me design
and think straight.

17:03.231 --> 17:04.857
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:04.857 --> 17:06.984
<i>So I've got this pencil topper</i>
<i>that I call Fred.</i>

17:06.984 --> 17:08.819
He keeps my company,
he inspires me,

17:08.819 --> 17:10.905
and it's just a great little
thing to have around.

17:10.905 --> 17:13.574
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:13.574 --> 17:16.577
‐ Bladesmiths, you have just
90 minutes remaining

17:16.577 --> 17:18.079
to finish your work.

17:18.079 --> 17:19.497
[tools buzzing]

17:19.497 --> 17:21.165
Now let's talk a little bit
about florets.

17:21.165 --> 17:22.416
‐ It's a decorative.

17:22.416 --> 17:24.710
My big concern
doing the testing

17:24.710 --> 17:26.504
is that they round those edges
off

17:26.504 --> 17:29.090
so there's not sharp angles
cutting into our hands.

17:29.090 --> 17:30.049
‐ Okay.

17:30.049 --> 17:31.801
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:31.801 --> 17:33.970
<i>‐ Things are actually going</i>
<i>pretty well.</i>

17:33.970 --> 17:35.846
So I start working
on my florets.

17:35.846 --> 17:38.516
<i>These are important. They're</i>
<i>one of the two requirements</i>

17:38.516 --> 17:42.478
to the...jambalaya?
No, that's the food.

17:42.478 --> 17:44.021
<i>Anyway,</i>
<i>to make the florets,</i>

17:44.021 --> 17:45.690
<i>the first thing I do is</i>
<i>I make four holes</i>

17:45.690 --> 17:47.525
<i>in two pieces</i>
<i>of relatively thin brass.</i>

17:47.525 --> 17:50.027
And I need to make
this look like a flower.

17:50.027 --> 17:51.529
[whirring]

17:51.529 --> 17:54.031
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:54.031 --> 17:55.908
It makes a horrible noise
but, you know,

17:55.908 --> 17:58.202
that's why I've got headphones
on: so I can't hear anything.

17:58.202 --> 17:59.453
[chuckling]

17:59.453 --> 18:01.372
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:01.372 --> 18:04.208
<i>‐ For our handles, we have</i>
<i>to use natural material,</i>

18:04.208 --> 18:06.252
so I find some ash wood.

18:06.252 --> 18:08.879
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:08.879 --> 18:12.383
But the pins are just not
fitting though my tang.

18:12.383 --> 18:13.676
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:13.676 --> 18:16.095
And I have to resize
my pinholes fast.

18:16.095 --> 18:17.221
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:17.221 --> 18:18.723
[chuckling]

18:18.723 --> 18:21.058
I get it large enough,
and it's finally able to fit

18:21.058 --> 18:22.101
with a larger pin stock,

18:22.101 --> 18:24.562
<i>but that was time wasted</i>

18:24.562 --> 18:27.356
and I still have
a fair amount of work to do.

18:27.356 --> 18:29.984
[whirring]

18:29.984 --> 18:33.571
‐ Chris has got a huge piece
of antler right there.

18:33.571 --> 18:34.780
What do you think, J.?

18:34.780 --> 18:36.407
‐ It's already very,
very wide.

18:36.407 --> 18:39.160
A piece of wood would be
a lot easier.

18:39.160 --> 18:40.995
‐ Once my slabs are cut
and flattened,

18:40.995 --> 18:42.622
I need to put some holes
in my knife.

18:42.622 --> 18:45.916
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:45.916 --> 18:48.419
‐ What is happening over there?

18:48.419 --> 18:50.004
‐ Nothing good.

18:50.004 --> 18:51.756
<i>‐ Sometimes when you're</i>
<i>drilling through steel</i>

18:51.756 --> 18:53.591
and it's sort of hard,
you can force your way through

18:53.591 --> 18:55.426
with enough cutting oil
and patience.

18:55.426 --> 18:57.178
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:57.178 --> 18:58.220
[bleep]!

18:58.220 --> 18:59.513
That's not working for me.

18:59.513 --> 19:01.932
‐ I've got a big concern
with Chris.

19:01.932 --> 19:03.726
‐ If I don't get
this hole drilled,

19:03.726 --> 19:06.020
I can't put my handle on,
and that means I'm going home.

19:06.020 --> 19:07.313
[whirring]

19:07.313 --> 19:08.856
‐ And the danger by that,
ultimately,

19:08.856 --> 19:10.566
is he doesn't know
how hot that's getting.

19:10.566 --> 19:12.652
‐ I'm seeing smoke
coming off it.

19:12.652 --> 19:19.450
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:19.450 --> 19:22.078
‐ What is happening over there?

19:22.078 --> 19:23.496
‐ I'm seeing smoke coming off
of it.

19:23.496 --> 19:26.290
‐ Did it work?
‐ Nope.

19:26.290 --> 19:28.668
‐ If the steel's too hard,
there's only one thing to do.

19:28.668 --> 19:30.461
[hissing]

19:30.461 --> 19:33.130
‐ Chris is trying to kill
the temper on that hole.

19:33.130 --> 19:34.548
[rattling]

19:34.548 --> 19:35.883
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:35.883 --> 19:37.468
‐ Yes!

19:37.468 --> 19:40.304
‐ Bladesmiths, 30 minutes!

19:40.304 --> 19:42.348
<i>‐ I finally decide that</i>
<i>I'm just going to commit</i>

19:42.348 --> 19:43.766
and assemble my handle.

19:43.766 --> 19:45.309
<i>J. is going to be brutal</i>
<i>on this,</i>

19:45.309 --> 19:47.603
so I have to make sure
that it's comfortable

19:47.603 --> 19:50.356
and isn't going to hurt
a judge's hand.

19:50.356 --> 19:52.066
[tapping]

19:52.066 --> 19:53.192
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:53.192 --> 19:54.777
‐ It's go time.

19:54.777 --> 19:58.322
I got to get these stupid
florets attached to my handle.

19:58.322 --> 19:59.824
[bleep]!

19:59.824 --> 20:02.952
Working these small florets is
a pain in the behind.

20:02.952 --> 20:04.995
<i>The ideal scenario</i>
<i>for attaching florets</i>

20:04.995 --> 20:08.624
is having plenty
of pin stock to peen over,

20:08.624 --> 20:10.209
<i>like Matt.</i>

20:10.209 --> 20:11.961
For me,
that's not the case.

20:11.961 --> 20:15.172
<i>The florets are on the floor.</i>
<i>Time is running out.</i>

20:15.172 --> 20:17.341
<i>Everything is</i>
<i>not going right.</i>

20:17.341 --> 20:19.260
‐ Dios mío, man.

20:19.260 --> 20:20.636
<i>‐ Even for Chris.</i>

20:20.636 --> 20:22.054
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:22.054 --> 20:23.597
<i>‐ Once I have the florets</i>
<i>fitted up,</i>

20:23.597 --> 20:25.516
I realize I've made
a critical mistake.

20:25.516 --> 20:26.767
‐ He's not going to be able

20:26.767 --> 20:28.144
to shape that panel anymore,
is he?

20:28.144 --> 20:29.687
‐ Chris is just realizing now

20:29.687 --> 20:31.856
that his florets
aren't going to lay flat.

20:31.856 --> 20:33.858
Instead of a flat piece
of material,

20:33.858 --> 20:35.484
he's got that raised antler,

20:35.484 --> 20:38.195
unlike the other guys,
who have flat pieces of wood.

20:38.195 --> 20:40.197
They could just lay
the florets flat.

20:40.197 --> 20:41.490
‐ The pins are glued there.

20:41.490 --> 20:42.825
There's no starting over
with that.

20:42.825 --> 20:44.702
<i>So I have to work around</i>
<i>the pins</i>

20:44.702 --> 20:48.414
<i>and try and grind down some</i>
<i>of this material really fast.</i>

20:48.414 --> 20:49.874
‐ Five minutes!

20:49.874 --> 20:51.709
<i>‐ I have my florets</i>
<i>attached now,</i>

20:51.709 --> 20:54.545
but I haven't sharpened
my blade.

20:54.545 --> 20:59.300
‐ Five, four, three, two, one!

20:59.300 --> 21:00.926
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines,

21:00.926 --> 21:02.303
drop your tools!

21:02.303 --> 21:05.014
This round of competition
is over!

21:05.014 --> 21:06.891
[applause]

21:06.891 --> 21:09.393
‐ The handle, it's enormous.
It's too fat.

21:09.393 --> 21:10.895
<i>It's going to be really</i>
<i>uncomfortable</i>

21:10.895 --> 21:12.229
<i>and hard to hold.</i>
<i>I don't know</i>

21:12.229 --> 21:13.647
<i>if I'm going to move on</i>
<i>or not.</i>

21:13.647 --> 21:15.149
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:15.149 --> 21:17.902
‐ Bladesmiths, welcome
to another strength test.

21:17.902 --> 21:19.570
Today, we're going to do
the horn chop.

21:19.570 --> 21:22.072
What I'm gonna do is take
your blades

21:22.072 --> 21:23.699
and test both edges

21:23.699 --> 21:26.368
in vertical and horizontal
chops on these horns.

21:26.368 --> 21:29.538
Now, what happens to your
horns? I really don't care.

21:29.538 --> 21:31.749
I wanna see what the horns
are gonna do to your knives.

21:31.749 --> 21:33.250
Ready, Matt?

21:33.250 --> 21:34.835
‐ No. [laughs]

21:34.835 --> 21:36.253
‐ Eh, we're gonna do it anyway.

21:36.253 --> 21:39.006
<i>‐ I am extremely nervous</i>
<i>about this test</i>

21:39.006 --> 21:42.426
<i>because horn is really,</i>
<i>really tough on blades</i>

21:42.426 --> 21:44.804
<i>and J. is gonna beat the crap</i>
<i>out of those horns</i>

21:44.804 --> 21:46.222
with our knives.

21:46.222 --> 21:48.557
Uh, uh, I just‐‐I don't know.
I'm scared.

21:48.557 --> 21:50.893
[groaning]
‐ [grunting]

21:50.893 --> 21:58.025
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:02.154 --> 22:03.823
‐ [sighing]

22:03.823 --> 22:04.865
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:04.865 --> 22:06.158
‐ Nice job, Matt.

22:06.158 --> 22:08.410
You handle's comfortable.
It's a good size.

22:08.410 --> 22:10.079
The only problem is
it's‐‐it's spinning.

22:10.079 --> 22:11.705
Striking the horn,
it turned on me.

22:11.705 --> 22:13.332
I had to readjust
a couple of times,

22:13.332 --> 22:15.000
but overall, very good job.

22:15.000 --> 22:16.377
‐ Thank you.

22:16.377 --> 22:17.962
‐ So after seeing that,
how do you feel, Chris?

22:17.962 --> 22:19.839
‐ Let's get this over with.
‐ [chuckling]

22:19.839 --> 22:22.800
<i>‐ The shock that that horn is</i>
<i>gonna send up the knife‐‐</i>

22:22.800 --> 22:25.052
<i>if anything's loose,</i>
<i>it's gonna come flying off.</i>

22:25.052 --> 22:26.470
I really wouldn't want
to be the one

22:26.470 --> 22:27.763
swinging my knife right now.

22:27.763 --> 22:30.975
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:30.975 --> 22:33.352
‐ [grunting]

22:33.352 --> 22:37.857
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:37.857 --> 22:39.275
‐ [inhales sharply]

22:39.275 --> 22:41.735
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:41.735 --> 22:43.445
‐ [grunting]

22:43.445 --> 22:47.491
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:47.491 --> 22:49.034
[pants]

22:49.034 --> 22:50.661
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:50.661 --> 22:52.913
‐ You okay?
‐ I'll be fine.

22:52.913 --> 22:55.332
‐ [sighing]

22:55.332 --> 22:57.167
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:57.167 --> 23:02.590
‐ Well, Chris, I cannot hold it
comfortably like this at all,

23:02.590 --> 23:04.466
and it put a ton of strain
on my wrist.

23:04.466 --> 23:05.885
You know, like,
a fireball going off

23:05.885 --> 23:07.177
in my wrist right there.

23:07.177 --> 23:08.679
But your edge held up.

23:08.679 --> 23:10.556
Good work on that.
‐ Thank you.

23:10.556 --> 23:11.932
‐ How the nerves doing, Aaron?

23:11.932 --> 23:14.018
‐ Not too good, sir.
[chuckling]

23:14.018 --> 23:15.436
‐ All right, let's do it.

23:15.436 --> 23:21.066
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:21.066 --> 23:25.988
[grunting]

23:25.988 --> 23:33.078
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:34.496 --> 23:36.874
[grunts]

23:36.874 --> 23:38.208
‐ [exhales]

23:38.208 --> 23:41.545
‐ Well, Aaron, your blade edge
survived the horn.

23:41.545 --> 23:42.922
Good job on your heat treat.

23:42.922 --> 23:44.882
You don't have any deformation
on the edge,

23:44.882 --> 23:46.216
so good job.

23:46.216 --> 23:47.718
‐ Thank you.

23:47.718 --> 23:49.470
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:49.470 --> 23:53.891
‐ All right, bladesmiths,
this is the rib rack slice.

23:53.891 --> 23:57.436
A sharp edge should cut easily
through this rib rack.

23:57.436 --> 23:59.229
Matt, you're up first.
Are you ready for this?

23:59.229 --> 24:00.898
‐ [groans]
I got to be.

24:00.898 --> 24:02.066
‐ Of course.

24:02.066 --> 24:09.239
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:12.326 --> 24:13.327
‐ Whoa.

24:13.327 --> 24:14.870
‐ Good job, man.

24:14.870 --> 24:16.205
‐ Thanks.

24:16.205 --> 24:17.414
‐ All right, Matt,

24:17.414 --> 24:18.832
this is a very sharp edge.

24:18.832 --> 24:22.586
Not only did it cut the muscles
in between the ribs,

24:22.586 --> 24:23.712
it cut the bone.

24:23.712 --> 24:26.006
Your handle construction
is smooth.

24:26.006 --> 24:28.759
Overall, sir,
your jambiya will cut.

24:28.759 --> 24:30.052
‐ Thank you.

24:30.052 --> 24:31.804
‐ All right, Chris,
you're up next. You ready?

24:31.804 --> 24:33.639
‐ Yes, please.
‐ Let's do this.

24:33.639 --> 24:36.767
‐ I want to apologize to Doug
for how bad this handle is,

24:36.767 --> 24:38.602
<i>but his hands are a little</i>
<i>smaller than J.'s.</i>

24:38.602 --> 24:40.437
<i>Maybe it'll fit</i>
<i>a little better.</i>

24:40.437 --> 24:43.399
I'm hoping he can work around
the deficiencies my knife has

24:43.399 --> 24:44.858
and make a good cut.

24:44.858 --> 24:51.991
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:54.618 --> 24:56.704
‐ All right, Chris, let's talk
about your jambiya here.

24:56.704 --> 24:59.373
Your blade is sharp enough
to cut through ribs,

24:59.373 --> 25:01.000
but then, your handle.

25:01.000 --> 25:03.544
When you hold it this way, it's
just too wide to be comfortable

25:03.544 --> 25:05.129
in holding on to it.

25:05.129 --> 25:07.464
But overall, sir,
your jambiya?

25:07.464 --> 25:08.799
It will cut.

25:08.799 --> 25:10.175
‐ Thank you.

25:10.175 --> 25:11.885
‐ Aaron, your turn.
You ready for this?

25:11.885 --> 25:13.429
‐ Yes, sir.
‐ Let's do this.

25:13.429 --> 25:20.561
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:28.444 --> 25:30.446
All right, Aaron, let's talk
about your blade here.

25:30.446 --> 25:32.322
Your edge on the outer curve
right here

25:32.322 --> 25:34.450
is sharp to cut through bone.

25:34.450 --> 25:38.037
Now, your inward curve right
here is sharp enough to cut,

25:38.037 --> 25:41.290
but not cut completely
all the way into the rib rack.

25:41.290 --> 25:43.292
I can index well
when I grab on to it,

25:43.292 --> 25:46.253
and your jambiya,
it will cut.

25:46.253 --> 25:48.088
‐ Thank you.

25:48.088 --> 25:50.632
<i>Ultimately, I think it's going</i>
<i>to come down to Chris' handle</i>

25:50.632 --> 25:53.093
or my knife not cutting on
the second swipe.

25:53.093 --> 25:55.345
<i>I'm pretty nervous about it.</i>

25:55.345 --> 25:56.847
<i>‐ I'd really like</i>
<i>to move forward.</i>

25:56.847 --> 25:59.016
I would really like
to redeem myself here,

25:59.016 --> 26:01.185
but it's still anyone's game.

26:01.185 --> 26:04.813
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

26:04.813 --> 26:07.858
‐ Bladesmiths, the judges'
deliberation is complete.

26:07.858 --> 26:10.402
They've made
their final decision.

26:13.906 --> 26:15.282
The fifth bladesmithesmith

26:15.282 --> 26:17.785
leaving this redemption
competition is...

26:17.785 --> 26:20.579
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:20.579 --> 26:22.539
Chris.

26:22.539 --> 26:24.666
I'm going to go ahead
and let J. Neilson explain.

26:24.666 --> 26:27.211
‐ Okay, so Aaron,
during the sharpness test,

26:27.211 --> 26:28.962
your blade did not cut
completely through

26:28.962 --> 26:31.298
on the second strike.
The thing about it, though,

26:31.298 --> 26:34.259
is Doug can walk away
unharmed

26:34.259 --> 26:36.011
and keep cutting with
that knife.

26:36.011 --> 26:39.223
Chris, your blade is sharp.
It's a good blade.

26:39.223 --> 26:41.975
But the handle is totally
uncomfortable.

26:41.975 --> 26:43.977
It cannot be held correctly.

26:43.977 --> 26:46.897
I actually hurt my wrist
using it

26:46.897 --> 26:48.941
and it's been in an ice pack
since testing,

26:48.941 --> 26:51.068
and we can't have a weapon
that's going to hurt the user.

26:51.068 --> 26:52.694
And that's why we're going
to let you go.

26:52.694 --> 26:54.071
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:54.071 --> 26:57.074
‐ Chris,
please surrender your blade.

26:57.074 --> 26:58.992
<i>‐ You get a second chance</i>
<i>at redemption,</i>

26:58.992 --> 27:00.577
<i>and you don't wanna</i>
<i>squander it.</i>

27:00.577 --> 27:02.704
I made a bad decision,
and it hurt J.'s wrist.

27:02.704 --> 27:03.956
I feel really bad about that.

27:03.956 --> 27:05.249
I'm sorry.
‐ It's okay.

27:05.249 --> 27:06.708
‐ Winning or losing
this competition

27:06.708 --> 27:08.460
isn't going to shake me
from my path.

27:08.460 --> 27:10.587
I'm going to keep making knives
and doing blacksmithing

27:10.587 --> 27:12.214
<i>and teaching classes.</i>

27:12.214 --> 27:14.133
I'm not gonna burn down my shop
and take up crochet.

27:14.133 --> 27:16.093
<i>The first thing I'm gonna do</i>
<i>when I get home</i>

27:16.093 --> 27:17.970
is hug my family,
tell them I love them,

27:17.970 --> 27:20.389
thank them for their support,
and take a really long nap.

27:20.389 --> 27:23.684
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:23.684 --> 27:25.602
‐ Matt, Aaron, congratulations.

27:25.602 --> 27:26.937
You've made it
to the final round

27:26.937 --> 27:28.605
of this
redemption competition.

27:28.605 --> 27:30.440
You guys have been through
hell,

27:30.440 --> 27:32.401
but now we're sending
you back to your home forges

27:32.401 --> 27:35.279
to recreate an iconic weapon
from history.

27:35.279 --> 27:37.614
The road to redemption
is never a straight one,

27:37.614 --> 27:39.908
so we're going to do things
a little differently.

27:39.908 --> 27:41.493
For the first time ever,

27:41.493 --> 27:44.371
we're going to tell you
what the final tests will be.

27:44.371 --> 27:47.457
J. will be testing your blades
for strength and durability

27:47.457 --> 27:50.627
against an old‐aged
oak whiskey barrel.

27:50.627 --> 27:53.005
Ben will be testing
your blades for sharpness

27:53.005 --> 27:54.882
against the wicker man,

27:54.882 --> 27:57.384
and, of course, Doug will be
testing your blades against

27:57.384 --> 27:59.386
a pig carcass
in the KEAL test.

27:59.386 --> 28:03.307
Well, you know the tests.
You know your judges.

28:03.307 --> 28:05.893
There's only one more decision
that you need to make.

28:05.893 --> 28:12.983
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:13.317 --> 28:14.818
‐ [exhales]

28:14.818 --> 28:16.528
<i>‐ Are we gonna have</i>
<i>to make multiple blades,</i>

28:16.528 --> 28:18.071
or are we gonna pick one?

28:18.071 --> 28:19.364
[stuttering]
What's going on here?

28:19.364 --> 28:20.741
‐ Gentlemen,
this is a selection

28:20.741 --> 28:22.159
of European weapons
from history

28:22.159 --> 28:24.494
that includes a claymore,
an arming sword,

28:24.494 --> 28:27.956
a karabela, a zweihander,
a cinquedea,

28:27.956 --> 28:29.207
and a kopis.

28:29.207 --> 28:31.043
You must choose one
of these weapons

28:31.043 --> 28:32.794
to forge at your home forge.

28:32.794 --> 28:35.547
What you don't know is
that you only have four days

28:35.547 --> 28:37.215
in which to complete
this challenge.

28:37.215 --> 28:39.176
Redemption,
you got to go through

28:39.176 --> 28:40.886
the dirt and mud to get it.

28:40.886 --> 28:43.347
<i>‐ Five days was barely enough</i>
<i>to finish my lion spear,</i>

28:43.347 --> 28:48.810
and so four days for a sword is
gonna be really tight.

28:48.810 --> 28:50.854
‐ We don't wanna know which
weapon you choose,

28:50.854 --> 28:53.106
but more importantly,
we don't want your opponent

28:53.106 --> 28:54.858
to know which weapon
you'll be forging.

28:54.858 --> 28:57.444
We just expect you
to choose wisely.

28:57.444 --> 29:01.031
‐ There's long swords, there's
short pigtail‐looking blades,

29:01.031 --> 29:02.908
<i>there's kukri‐like blades,</i>

29:02.908 --> 29:05.702
<i>and they're all going</i>
<i>to be challenging,</i>

29:05.702 --> 29:08.413
<i>but knowing what the tests</i>
<i>are ahead of time</i>

29:08.413 --> 29:11.291
puts a really good plan
in my mind,

29:11.291 --> 29:14.544
<i>knowing that I need something</i>
<i>that's going to be durable</i>

29:14.544 --> 29:16.213
and still retain
its sharp edge.

29:16.213 --> 29:19.257
‐ Good luck, bladesmiths.
We'll see you in four days.

29:19.257 --> 29:21.259
‐ Good luck, man,
‐ Thanks buddy, you too.

29:21.259 --> 29:23.929
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:23.929 --> 29:26.848
<i>‐ Feels really good to be back</i>
<i>in the final round.</i>

29:26.848 --> 29:28.058
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:28.058 --> 29:29.476
<i>The game plan for day one</i>

29:29.476 --> 29:32.187
is to get all the forging
on the sword done.

29:32.187 --> 29:33.522
[whirring]

29:33.522 --> 29:35.065
I chose an arming sword.

29:35.065 --> 29:38.068
<i>It's a type of sword</i>
<i>I'm very familiar with,</i>

29:38.068 --> 29:41.405
<i>and I think this weapon</i>
<i>has a good chance</i>

29:41.405 --> 29:43.740
<i>of doing well</i>
<i>on the two cutting tests</i>

29:43.740 --> 29:46.702
<i>and surviving</i>
<i>J.'s barrel test.</i>

29:46.702 --> 29:51.581
<i>What I hope to prove is that</i>
<i>I really am a very good smith</i>

29:51.581 --> 29:54.418
and that I'm not a loser.

29:54.418 --> 29:56.795
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:56.795 --> 29:58.964
‐ I'm back home.
I'm in the final round!

29:58.964 --> 30:01.008
I told you, Mom,
I could do it.

30:01.008 --> 30:04.261
<i>I get to make a finale weapon</i>
<i>of my own choice,</i>

30:04.261 --> 30:05.637
<i>which is amazing.</i>

30:05.637 --> 30:07.305
We got home‐field
advantage now.

30:07.305 --> 30:08.265
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:08.265 --> 30:10.100
<i>I chose the Greek kopis.</i>

30:10.100 --> 30:11.643
<i>This is an all‐around blade.</i>

30:11.643 --> 30:13.353
<i>It can do just</i>
<i>about anything,</i>

30:13.353 --> 30:15.272
and it's going to be
very durable.

30:15.272 --> 30:19.317
<i>This kopis is going to be</i>
<i>perfect for chopping on a hog.</i>

30:19.317 --> 30:21.236
At the end of day one,
I want to get

30:21.236 --> 30:24.531
<i>to a rough final profile</i>
<i>of my blade.</i>

30:24.531 --> 30:26.408
Oh, man.

30:26.408 --> 30:27.909
It's just not where
I want it.

30:27.909 --> 30:30.370
There's telltale signs
of overheating.

30:30.370 --> 30:33.331
There's what looks to be maybe
even surface cracks.

30:33.331 --> 30:36.960
<i>I'm not gonna know until I</i>
<i>start grinding it tomorrow.</i>

30:36.960 --> 30:38.378
Oh!

30:38.378 --> 30:39.755
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:39.755 --> 30:41.131
<i>‐ Today is fuller day.</i>

30:41.131 --> 30:43.091
<i>This is the hardest part</i>
<i>of the grind</i>

30:43.091 --> 30:44.968
because with
two medium fullers,

30:44.968 --> 30:46.803
you can actually grind
through your sword

30:46.803 --> 30:47.846
if you're not careful.

30:47.846 --> 30:50.807
<i>I establish them this way.</i>

30:50.807 --> 30:51.933
[grinding]

30:51.933 --> 30:53.393
<i>I've done fullers before,</i>

30:53.393 --> 30:55.687
<i>but I haven't done</i>
<i>ones this skinny.</i>

30:55.687 --> 30:57.355
I'm gonna take
this really slow,

30:57.355 --> 31:00.067
<i>make sure I avoid</i>
<i>grinding them too deep</i>

31:00.067 --> 31:01.818
and having them meet
in the middle.

31:01.818 --> 31:03.403
[grinding]

31:03.403 --> 31:05.322
Yeah, we're done.
We're done.

31:05.322 --> 31:06.490
It's good.

31:06.490 --> 31:07.866
[scraping]

31:07.866 --> 31:09.910
That's how thick the sword is

31:09.910 --> 31:12.162
in between those fullers,

31:12.162 --> 31:15.415
so that's why you have
to be really careful.

31:15.415 --> 31:18.001
<i>The concern I would have</i>
<i>about Aaron's choice</i>

31:18.001 --> 31:20.504
is that he would choose
the kopis

31:20.504 --> 31:23.548
<i>and he'd build it</i>
<i>really big and sturdy</i>

31:23.548 --> 31:27.344
and it would survive
the strength test

31:27.344 --> 31:28.428
better than mine.

31:28.428 --> 31:30.722
I like that.

31:30.722 --> 31:32.140
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:32.140 --> 31:33.600
<i>‐ Yesterday,</i>
<i>at the end of day one,</i>

31:33.600 --> 31:35.769
I didn't feel good at all
about my blade.

31:35.769 --> 31:37.646
<i>I need to see if my blade</i>
<i>has any cracks,</i>

31:37.646 --> 31:40.190
<i>and we'll only know once</i>
<i>I start grinding.</i>

31:40.190 --> 31:41.858
[whirring]

31:41.858 --> 31:43.777
<i>Winning this would mean</i>
<i>the world to me.</i>

31:43.777 --> 31:46.029
Like, this is my redemption.
I can't turn in

31:46.029 --> 31:47.364
a cracked blade to the judges.

31:47.364 --> 31:48.740
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:48.740 --> 31:50.575
<i>We've only got four days</i>
<i>to do things,</i>

31:50.575 --> 31:52.285
and if I see a crack
in my blade,

31:52.285 --> 31:53.703
day one is all for naught.

31:53.703 --> 31:55.330
<i>I'm gonna have to start over.</i>

31:55.330 --> 31:56.832
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:56.832 --> 31:59.376
I've got all these surface
stress cracks right here,

31:59.376 --> 32:01.044
and that's not good.

32:01.044 --> 32:02.963
I'm gonna have to start over.

32:02.963 --> 32:07.551
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:07.551 --> 32:09.219
<i>So I'm gonna re‐forge</i>
<i>another blade.</i>

32:09.219 --> 32:11.388
It sucks,

32:11.388 --> 32:12.889
but here we go.

32:12.889 --> 32:14.432
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:14.432 --> 32:17.310
<i>I'm going to take shorter</i>
<i>but hotter heats</i>

32:17.310 --> 32:19.229
<i>to maintain the heat</i>
<i>throughout the blade,</i>

32:19.229 --> 32:20.730
<i>and I'm hoping that</i>
<i>this strategy</i>

32:20.730 --> 32:23.358
<i>will not only produce</i>
<i>a blade quicker,</i>

32:23.358 --> 32:25.694
but also yield
a better blade as well.

32:25.694 --> 32:27.320
[scratching]

32:27.320 --> 32:28.989
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:28.989 --> 32:32.909
<i>‐ Now I got to move on</i>
<i>to getting the guard fitted</i>

32:32.909 --> 32:34.578
and getting that onto
the blade.

32:34.578 --> 32:38.665
I remember being taught
how to hot‐fit guards.

32:38.665 --> 32:42.711
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:42.711 --> 32:43.712
[pounding]

32:43.712 --> 32:45.213
Little on that end...

32:45.213 --> 32:46.590
[pounding]

32:46.590 --> 32:48.550
But that's good.
Now we wanna get it off

32:48.550 --> 32:51.636
before we transfer too much
heat to the blade.

32:51.636 --> 32:54.806
Come on, come on.
You can make it.

32:54.806 --> 32:56.933
Uh, see, I've...

32:56.933 --> 32:58.685
hammered it into the fuller.

32:58.685 --> 33:00.020
[banging]

33:00.020 --> 33:01.688
[clanging]

33:01.688 --> 33:02.814
[sighing]

33:02.814 --> 33:04.274
<i>I take a look at the blade,</i>

33:04.274 --> 33:06.526
<i>and there wasn't enough</i>
<i>heat transfer</i>

33:06.526 --> 33:09.112
to really do any damage,
so I'm in good shape.

33:09.112 --> 33:10.780
All right.

33:10.780 --> 33:12.199
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:12.199 --> 33:13.992
<i>‐ One of the things that</i>
<i>this blade has</i>

33:13.992 --> 33:16.786
<i>that is a requirement</i>
<i>is a knuckle‐bow.</i>

33:16.786 --> 33:18.538
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:18.538 --> 33:21.917
<i>My idea for the knuckle‐bow</i>
<i>is to take some mild steel</i>

33:21.917 --> 33:24.878
<i>and forge it on a forwards</i>
<i>and reverse taper</i>

33:24.878 --> 33:27.214
and tack‐weld it to the blade.

33:27.214 --> 33:29.174
[buzzing]

33:29.174 --> 33:30.884
I hope that sticks

33:30.884 --> 33:32.761
and it's not gonna
go anywhere.

33:32.761 --> 33:34.387
Fingers crossed.

33:34.387 --> 33:36.973
<i>Got it on, it‐‐it seems like</i>
<i>it's going to stay on,</i>

33:36.973 --> 33:41.353
and I have $20,000
counting on this blade.

33:41.353 --> 33:42.854
Cool!

33:42.854 --> 33:48.068
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:48.068 --> 33:49.819
‐ Gentlemen, welcome back.

33:49.819 --> 33:53.615
It's time to see what you guys
chose as your finale weapons.

33:53.615 --> 33:56.409
Matthew, you're up first.
Show us what you got.

33:56.409 --> 34:00.997
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:00.997 --> 34:04.292
All right, Matt, it looks like
you chose the arming sword.

34:04.292 --> 34:06.670
<i>The arming sword was</i>
<i>the weapon of choice</i>

34:06.670 --> 34:08.213
<i>for Medieval European knights</i>

34:08.213 --> 34:11.466
<i>primarily during</i>
<i>the 14th and 15th century.</i>

34:11.466 --> 34:13.718
<i>Wielded during an era</i>
<i>of advanced armor,</i>

34:13.718 --> 34:16.596
<i>its characteristic taper point</i>
<i>was built specifically</i>

34:16.596 --> 34:18.515
<i>for piercing</i>
<i>the small amounts of flesh</i>

34:18.515 --> 34:21.142
<i>that a knight left exposed.</i>

34:21.142 --> 34:23.645
<i>The quillons on the arming</i>
<i>sword defended the sword hand,</i>

34:23.645 --> 34:25.730
<i>leaving the other hand free</i>
<i>to hold a shield,</i>

34:25.730 --> 34:27.691
<i>dagger,</i>
<i>or even grab an opponent.</i>

34:27.691 --> 34:29.317
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:29.317 --> 34:31.444
All right, Aaron,
what did you bring for us?

34:31.444 --> 34:35.448
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:35.448 --> 34:37.450
Looks like the Greek kopis.

34:37.450 --> 34:39.077
‐ [mouths word]

34:39.077 --> 34:41.663
<i>‐ The Greek kopis dates back</i>
<i>to the 6th century B. C.</i>

34:41.663 --> 34:44.374
<i>and was the primary weapon</i>
<i>of Ancient Greek cavalry.</i>

34:44.374 --> 34:46.042
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:46.042 --> 34:48.378
<i>A curved blade with a heavy</i>
<i>and thick pointed tip,</i>

34:48.378 --> 34:50.380
<i>the weapon was used</i>
<i>to hack and thrust</i>

34:50.380 --> 34:52.048
<i>from a mounted position.</i>

34:52.048 --> 34:53.883
<i>Though only 20 inches long,</i>

34:53.883 --> 34:56.970
<i>the deadly kopis was used by</i>
<i>Alexander the Great's troops</i>

34:56.970 --> 35:01.558
<i>against enemy war elephants at</i>
<i>the Battle of Hydaspes.</i>

35:01.558 --> 35:03.184
<i>‐ Aaron chose the Greek kopis,</i>

35:03.184 --> 35:05.145
and I'm thinking that was
an excellent choice for him.

35:05.145 --> 35:07.564
<i>I think it's going to do great</i>
<i>on the barrel test.</i>

35:07.564 --> 35:09.107
My only concern is that

35:09.107 --> 35:11.067
it's going to be
better than mine. [laughs]

35:11.067 --> 35:13.069
‐ All right, gentlemen.

35:13.069 --> 35:16.156
This is the first time that
we've had two different blades

35:16.156 --> 35:18.199
engage in the same test.

35:18.199 --> 35:20.410
There's a strength test,
there's a sharpness test,

35:20.410 --> 35:23.121
and up first,
the KEAL test. Doug?

35:23.121 --> 35:24.748
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:24.748 --> 35:26.499
‐ All right, bladesmiths.
To find out

35:26.499 --> 35:28.126
what kind of lethal
damage your weapon will do,

35:28.126 --> 35:30.003
I will take your weapon,
delivering killing blows

35:30.003 --> 35:31.087
to this big carcass.

35:31.087 --> 35:32.380
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:32.380 --> 35:34.090
Matt, you're up first.
Are you ready for this?

35:34.090 --> 35:35.967
‐ Yeah, butcher it.
‐ Let's do it.

35:35.967 --> 35:37.093
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:37.093 --> 35:38.762
<i>‐ When it comes to</i>

35:38.762 --> 35:40.513
<i>cutting into the pig,</i>

35:40.513 --> 35:43.099
<i>that kopis is going to cut</i>
<i>deeper than my sword will,</i>

35:43.099 --> 35:45.935
but it's heavier, so it's‐‐
it's hard to know.

35:45.935 --> 35:52.817
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:58.615 --> 36:01.618
[sword ringing]

36:01.618 --> 36:03.244
‐ Yes!
[clapping]

36:03.244 --> 36:05.330
‐ [laughs] Brother!

36:05.330 --> 36:07.874
‐ First up,
this sword is sharp,

36:07.874 --> 36:10.752
but what I love about it
is the balance.

36:10.752 --> 36:14.130
You can move and fight
multiple opponents with it.

36:14.130 --> 36:16.591
Overall, sir, your sword?

36:16.591 --> 36:17.634
It will KEAL.

36:17.634 --> 36:18.885
‐ Thank you.

36:18.885 --> 36:21.054
‐ All right, Aaron,
it's your turn.

36:21.054 --> 36:22.472
Ready for this?
‐ Yes, sir.

36:22.472 --> 36:23.973
‐ Let's do it.

36:23.973 --> 36:26.976
<i>‐ I know this kopis</i>
<i>is going to be awesome.</i>

36:26.976 --> 36:28.436
<i>It's known to be a chopper,</i>

36:28.436 --> 36:30.230
<i>and it's known</i>
<i>for dismemberment.</i>

36:30.230 --> 36:34.192
It should be dismembering this
pig in probably two swipes.

36:34.192 --> 36:41.366
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:49.290 --> 36:50.542
Holy cow.

36:50.542 --> 36:51.835
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:51.835 --> 36:55.088
Yes.
[chuckling]

36:55.088 --> 36:56.589
Wow, that's amazing.

36:56.589 --> 36:58.550
‐ All right, Aaron,
let's talk about your kopis.

36:58.550 --> 37:00.135
It's a chopper.

37:00.135 --> 37:02.846
Ever slash digs deep
into this carcass.

37:02.846 --> 37:05.056
It's a very sharp blade.

37:05.056 --> 37:07.100
The balance feels good
with this,

37:07.100 --> 37:09.060
it cuts deep,
and most importantly,

37:09.060 --> 37:10.729
it will KEAL.

37:10.729 --> 37:12.105
‐ Thank you.

37:12.105 --> 37:15.275
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:15.275 --> 37:16.776
‐ [chuckling]

37:16.776 --> 37:18.570
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:18.570 --> 37:20.572
Bladesmiths,
welcome to one of our

37:20.572 --> 37:22.532
more devastating
strength tests:

37:22.532 --> 37:23.700
the barrel chop.

37:23.700 --> 37:25.368
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:25.368 --> 37:27.120
I'm gonna take both
of your swords

37:27.120 --> 37:28.872
and I'm going
to beat them mercilessly

37:28.872 --> 37:30.165
into this big old barrel.

37:30.165 --> 37:31.708
Matt, you're up first.
How you feeling?

37:31.708 --> 37:32.876
‐ Not good.

37:32.876 --> 37:34.294
‐ I feel healthy.

37:34.294 --> 37:35.378
‐ [chuckling]

37:35.378 --> 37:41.050
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:41.050 --> 37:42.469
‐ [grunting]

37:42.469 --> 37:49.601
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:52.520 --> 37:54.606
‐ Holy [bleep].

37:54.606 --> 37:56.065
‐ You got a really nice sword
here, Matt.

37:56.065 --> 37:58.067
You still got an edge.
No chipping,

37:58.067 --> 38:00.904
no wiggling.
Came right back to true.

38:00.904 --> 38:02.363
Everything's tight.
Very good job.

38:02.363 --> 38:03.615
‐ Thank you.

38:03.615 --> 38:05.200
‐ Aaron, how you feeling
after watching that?

38:05.200 --> 38:06.910
‐ I'm a little scared,
to be honest with you.

38:06.910 --> 38:08.953
‐ You'll get over it.
‐ [chuckling] Yes, sir.

38:08.953 --> 38:12.165
<i>Matt's blade survived,</i>
<i>and that's a thinner blade.</i>

38:12.165 --> 38:14.542
<i>This barrel could do anything</i>
<i>to my blade,</i>

38:14.542 --> 38:17.003
and, you know, that‐‐that
could be a game changer.

38:17.003 --> 38:23.843
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:23.843 --> 38:26.095
‐ [grunting]

38:26.095 --> 38:33.269
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:34.270 --> 38:35.939
‐ Oh, Lordy.
[sighing]

38:35.939 --> 38:37.941
[chuckling]

38:37.941 --> 38:41.319
‐ Well, Aaron, no chips.
Still have a sharp edge.

38:41.319 --> 38:42.320
Great job.

38:42.320 --> 38:43.446
‐ Thank you.

38:43.446 --> 38:45.865
‐ The handle?
Bit on the big side.

38:45.865 --> 38:48.827
The one problem I do have
is right here.

38:48.827 --> 38:51.913
Your little weld right there
broke loose.

38:51.913 --> 38:54.624
But otherwise, great blade.

38:54.624 --> 38:55.917
‐ Thank you.

38:55.917 --> 38:58.920
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:58.920 --> 39:00.129
‐ Bladesmiths,

39:00.129 --> 39:01.464
to test the sharpness
of your blades

39:01.464 --> 39:03.132
as well as their
overall construction,

39:03.132 --> 39:05.385
I'm going to cut the limbs
from these sugarcane men.

39:05.385 --> 39:06.469
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:06.469 --> 39:07.804
Matt, you're up first.
You ready?

39:07.804 --> 39:10.181
‐ Yup!
‐ Let's do this.

39:10.181 --> 39:12.809
<i>‐ Aaron and I are so close</i>
<i>at this point,</i>

39:12.809 --> 39:14.978
<i>that if there's</i>
<i>a significant difference</i>

39:14.978 --> 39:17.981
<i>between the way my blade cuts</i>
<i>and his blade cuts,</i>

39:17.981 --> 39:20.149
then it might all be over
for me.

39:20.149 --> 39:27.323
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:27.824 --> 39:29.492
‐ Oh, my gosh.

39:29.492 --> 39:30.869
‐ Well, Matt,
first thing's first:

39:30.869 --> 39:32.495
this is a beautifully
weighted weapon.

39:32.495 --> 39:34.163
I really enjoy swinging this.

39:34.163 --> 39:35.331
‐ Thank you.

39:35.331 --> 39:36.875
‐ It's very sharp.
You can see the‐‐

39:36.875 --> 39:40.003
the cuts on the sugarcane
are clean all the way through.

39:40.003 --> 39:41.838
Well done.
‐ Thanks.

39:41.838 --> 39:43.882
‐ Aaron, you're up.
You ready for this?

39:43.882 --> 39:46.676
‐ Yes, sir.
‐ All right.

39:46.676 --> 39:53.808
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:56.019 --> 39:58.688
<i>[rock music]</i>

39:58.688 --> 40:03.026
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:03.026 --> 40:05.028
‐ Dang tootin'.
[chuckling]

40:05.028 --> 40:06.654
‐ Well, Aaron,
this is certainly a chopper.

40:06.654 --> 40:08.990
It goes through the sugarcane
like it's not even there.

40:08.990 --> 40:10.617
There's no tearing,
no ripping, anything.

40:10.617 --> 40:13.202
It's just beautiful cuts all
the way around.

40:13.202 --> 40:16.289
This is a wicked‐sharp blade.
It's a hell of a cutter.

40:16.289 --> 40:18.333
Well done.
‐ Thank you.

40:18.333 --> 40:19.626
This has
been a kick‐butt blade!

40:19.626 --> 40:21.252
That's for sure!

40:21.252 --> 40:23.171
<i>This thing hacks and slashes</i>
<i>and cuts sugarcane</i>

40:23.171 --> 40:24.756
<i>and it's severing pigs</i>
<i>in half.</i>

40:24.756 --> 40:26.799
<i>It's a really killer blade,</i>

40:26.799 --> 40:29.802
<i>but Matt's blade</i>
<i>is pretty much perfect.</i>

40:29.802 --> 40:31.137
It's really a close call.

40:31.137 --> 40:33.723
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:33.723 --> 40:38.102
‐ Bladesmiths, the judges'
deliberation is complete.

40:38.102 --> 40:41.314
The road to redemption is not
an easy road to travel,

40:41.314 --> 40:43.566
and you guys have been up
against obstacles

40:43.566 --> 40:44.817
the entire way.

40:44.817 --> 40:47.612
The fire, the steel,
the clock.

40:47.612 --> 40:49.364
We thank you for all
of your hard work.

40:49.364 --> 40:50.782
I'm very proud of you.

40:50.782 --> 40:52.367
Our new "Forged in Fire"
champion

40:52.367 --> 40:56.579
and the recipient
of that $20,000 check is...

40:56.579 --> 40:59.457
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:59.457 --> 41:03.044
Matt, congratulations. You're
the "Forged in Fire" champion.

41:03.044 --> 41:06.172
Aaron, unfortunately, your
blade didn't make the cut.

41:06.172 --> 41:08.466
‐ Aaron,
you produced a great blade

41:08.466 --> 41:09.884
that performed very well,

41:09.884 --> 41:12.053
but your handle was
on the large side

41:12.053 --> 41:14.305
and, more importantly,
a piece of it broke.

41:14.305 --> 41:16.516
And for that reason,
we're sending you home.

41:16.516 --> 41:18.768
‐ Aaron, I'm very proud
of you, young man,

41:18.768 --> 41:20.770
but at this time
I have to ask you

41:20.770 --> 41:22.271
to please surrender that kopis.

41:22.271 --> 41:23.940
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:23.940 --> 41:26.275
<i>‐ The devil's in the details,</i>
<i>and it really shows.</i>

41:26.275 --> 41:29.404
<i>Matt just did a few things</i>
<i>better than I did,</i>

41:29.404 --> 41:30.738
and then‐‐you know,

41:30.738 --> 41:32.532
that's ultimately
what it came down to.

41:32.532 --> 41:35.410
Understanding what blessings
are around you goes a long way,

41:35.410 --> 41:37.704
and Matt's a really big
blessing in my life

41:37.704 --> 41:40.123
<i>and being able</i>
<i>to compete with him</i>

41:40.123 --> 41:42.583
as well as the rest of the
amazing smiths in this journey.

41:42.583 --> 41:44.460
<i>I'm very thankful for each</i>
<i>and every one of them.</i>

41:44.460 --> 41:46.754
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:46.754 --> 41:48.131
‐ Matt, congratulations.

41:48.131 --> 41:49.924
You are
the "Forged in Fire" champion

41:49.924 --> 41:54.971
and this redemption title comes
with a check for $20,000.

41:54.971 --> 41:55.972
Good job, my friend.

41:55.972 --> 41:57.807
‐ Whoo!
[applause]

41:57.807 --> 42:00.977
‐ Matt, please present
your blade to the judges.

42:00.977 --> 42:03.813
‐ I‐‐I kind of, uh‐‐
[babbles comically]

42:03.813 --> 42:06.024
I don't have words for this.

42:06.024 --> 42:07.650
<i>I came here,</i>
<i>I redeemed myself,</i>

42:07.650 --> 42:09.652
<i>and I'm the new</i>
<i>"Forged in Fire" champion,</i>

42:09.652 --> 42:11.946
and I am totally pumped!

42:11.946 --> 42:13.489
<i>♪ ♪</i>

42:13.489 --> 42:15.116
Don't put that on TV.

42:15.116 --> 42:21.581
<i>♪ ♪</i>
